-- South African Stocks Fall, Led Down by Anglo, BHP Billiton, Lonmin, Telkom
-- B y   S i k o n a t h i   M a n t s h a n t s h a
-- 2010-11-10T17:13:27Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-10/south-african-stocks-fall-led-by-anglo-american-billiton-sasol-telkom.html
South Africa’s  FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index  fell for a second time this week, losing 144.31, or
0.5 percent, to 31,517.83 at the 5 p.m. close in Johannesburg.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.  BHP Billiton Plc  (BIL SJ), the world’s largest mining
company, declined the most since Aug. 18, retreating 6.70 rand,
or 2.5 percent, to 265.60 rand. Copper slipped as much as 2.2
percent to $8,660.25 a metric ton on the London Metal Exchange.
Lead and nickel also fell.  Anglo American Plc  (AGL SJ), the
diversified mining company that makes up 10 percent of South
Africa’s benchmark stock index, decreased 3.38 rand, or 1
percent, to 327.60 rand.  Anglo Platinum Ltd.  (AMS SJ), the world’s largest producer
of the precious metal, declined the most in two weeks, slumping
11.50 rand, or 1.6 percent, to 708.50 rand. Platinum slid as
much as 4.3 percent to $1,728.05 an ounce.  Impala Platinum
Holdings Ltd.  (IMP SJ), the second-biggest, lost 2.69 rand, or
1.3 percent, to 213 rand.  Business Connexion Group  (BCX SJ), an information and
communications technology company, climbed 55 cents, or 8.7
percent, to 6.90 rand, snapping three days of decreases. The
company said profit attributable to shareholders rose 15 percent
to 123.3 million rand ($17.9 million) in the year through
August.  Lewis Group Ltd.  (LEW SJ), a furniture and electrical goods
retailer, advanced for the third consecutive day, rising 1.09
rand, or 1.5 percent, to 75.95 rand, the highest since at least
October 2004. The retailer was raised to “buy” from “hold”
at Citigroup Inc.  Lonmin Plc  (LON SJ), the world’s third-largest platinum
producer, slid 5 rand, or 2.4 percent, to 202 rand, the lowest
in a week. The National Union of Mineworkers rejected Lonmin’s
revised offer of a 7.2 percent pay increase.  Merafe Resources Ltd.  (MRF SJ), a ferrochrome producer,
advanced 14 cents, or 9.8 percent, to 1.57 rand, the highest
since June 2. Stainless-steel production, which requires
ferrochrome, is expected to reach record levels this year, it
said in a presentation on its  website  today.  Telkom SA Ltd.  (TKG SJ), Africa’s largest fixed-line
telephone-network operator, dropped 86 cents, or 2.3 percent, to
35.84 rand, the lowest since Sept. 20. The company said it may
post a first-half loss.  Vodacom Group Ltd.  (VOD SJ), South Africa’s largest mobile-
network operator, rose for the third consecutive day, gaining
1.19 rand, or 1.7 percent, to 70.69 rand. Vodacom’s price
estimate was raised to 76 rand from 72 rand at Morgan Stanley.
 MTN Group Ltd.  (MTN SJ), Africa’s biggest operator, gained 1.8
rand, or 1.4 percent, to 129.50 rand.  To contact the reporter on this story:
